			                <h1>CBCAC</h1>
                                <audio src="/audio/en/cbcac.mp3" controls>
                                    Recording of CBCAC article
                                </audio>
			<p><br>In 1998, the Chinese American Service League (CASL), Chinese Consolidated Benevolent Association (CCBA), Chinatown Chamber of Commerce, Pui Tak Center, and Chinese Christian Union Church (CCUC) formed the Coalition for a Better Chinatown (CBC), now called the Coalition for a Better Chinese American Community, in order to fight against presence and marketing of casinos in the community. <br> <br />
			    In 2000 CBCAC worked on a project called “Asian American Vote 2000”. The goal of the project was to encourage the community to vote and gain political power to make needed changes in the Chinatown community. <br> <br />
			    CBCAC advocated for a single legislative district for setting an agenda for elections. Since the community didn’t have power for more than 100 years, CBCAC and Chinatown community members came up with a list of things the community needed. The most important were what became the Chinatown Branch of the Chicago Public Library,Leonard M. Louie Fisher Field House, and Ping Tom Park. In ten years, they accomplished all of their goals. <br> <br />
			    CBCAC collaborated with the Chicago Metropolitan Agency for Planning on making the Chinatown Vision Plan project. In pursuance of community needs, CBCAC took inputs from more than 1,000 community members. <br> <br />
			    Currently, they are implementing a Chinatown Vision Plan project. It includes plans for education, transportation, infrastructure, parking, safety, and social and economic aspects of Chinatown. <br> <br />
			    Youth in Chinatown play a very important role in CBCAC. Young volunteers from local high schools helped in promoting the importance of elections by talking with community members. They registered more than 16,000 voters. CBCAC’s youth group, ORIGIN, has been organizing a community meeting to discuss the Chinatown community’s problems and solutions.</p>
